    <bioghist encodinganalog="545">
      <head>Biographical History</head>
      <p>The Office of Price Stabilization (1950-1953), also known as the Price Stabilization 
		Board, was a federal agency tasked with controlling prices during the Korean War.  A 
		Director of Price Stabilization was named in late 1950 and the OPS was formally established 
		in January of 1951.    Through its 14 regional and about 90 district offices, the OPS obtained voluntary compliance with measures to stabilize prices and established and 
		administered price regulations.</p>
    </bioghist>
    <scopecontent encodinganalog="520">
      <head>Scope and Contents of the Collection</head>
      <p>The <emph render="bold">Office of Price Stabilization Records</emph> contain general 
		files and published material.</p><p><emph render="bold">General files</emph> includes lists of stores and industries in 
		Syracuse and the surrounding area that produce goods or provide services covered by the OPS 
		mandate.  There is also some business correspondence and miscellaneous material.</p>
		
		<p><emph render="bold">Published material</emph> contains several volumes of government publications and correspondence.</p>
    </scopecontent>
    <arrangement encodinganalog="351$a">
      <head>Arrangement of the Collection</head>
      <p>General files are arranged alphabetically by topic.  Published material is subdivided by type (books, pamphlets, volumes) and arranged alphabetically by title.</p>
    </arrangement>
